            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Oyelowo\u2019s story began in Oakland, a city subtly different yet inherently linked to San Francisco. He was raised by supportive parents; his mother, a nurse, instilled in him empathy and patience, while his father, a jazz musician, nurtured his creative spirit. Growing up, David found solace and expression in art \u2013 drawing, painting, even sculpting. It was a private world he retreated into, especially during the challenging years of navigating teenage angst and racial identity in a diverse but sometimes segregated city.\n\nHis undergraduate degree in Fine Arts laid the groundwork, but it was during his Master of Fine Arts in Art Education that David discovered his true calling. He recognized the power of art not just as expression, but as a therapeutic tool. This epiphany led him to pivot, integrating art therapy into his studies. He developed a profound understanding of how creative processes could heal and empower individuals.\n\nA significant turning point arrived during a volunteer placement at a San Francisco youth center. Witnessing the profound impact of guided art sessions on troubled teens solidified his career path. Graduating, he secured a position that blended his passions: working as an Art Therapist across educational, healthcare, and social service settings within San Francisco. He helps diverse populations \u2013 from children struggling with trauma to adults managing mental health challenges \u2013 providing a safe space for them to communicate and process through creative means.\n\nDavid\u2019s connections in San Francisco are deep-rooted. He lives in the Mission District, drawn to its vibrant energy and strong sense of community. His daily routine often involves a scenic 3.1-mile bike ride to his various workplaces, a ritual that clears his head and connects him to the city's rhythm. He maintains close relationships with his family in Oakland and has a tight-knit circle of friends, many of whom he met through work or shared cultural interests in the city\u2019s dynamic arts scene.\n\nLooking ahead, David dreams of establishing a non-profit organization dedicated to providing accessible art therapy services to underserved communities across the Bay Area. He envisions a space where art can be a catalyst for social change and individual healing. His current lifestyle, though busy, allows him to pursue these aspirations, fueled by the belief that creativity holds immense power, a power he is dedicated to sharing with the people of San Francisco."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The day he first saw a teenager, usually withdrawn and silent, pour their hurt onto the canvas with furious, vibrant strokes at the youth center. A wave of profound purpose washed over him \u2013 this was more than art; it was voice, it was healing. It solidified his career path entirely, making the struggle of graduate school feel utterly worth it. This was early in his Art Therapy career, confirming his calling.\n\n2. Biking across the Golden Gate Bridge as the fog rolled in one crisp morning. The vastness of the bay, the quiet hum of fellow cyclists, the feeling of gliding \u2013 it wasn\u2019t just exercise; it was mental clarity, a moving meditation. It became a vital ritual, his personal reset button, grounding him in the city he served. This memory is ongoing, a consistent source of peace.\n\n3. Sharing his detailed plan for a community art therapy space with his parents over a home-cooked Oakland dinner. Their quiet pride, his father's knowing nod about the power of creative expression \u2013 it fueled his ambition and eased any self-doubt. Their belief affirmed his vision and strengthened his resolve to make it happen. This happened recently, as his non-profit dream began taking shape.\n\n4. Standing in the vibrant chaos of a Mission District street fair, watching children paint murals on a temporary wall. Their uninhibited joy, the way art broke down barriers between strangers \u2013 it mirrored the inclusive community he loved and felt a part of. It reinforced his belief in art's power to unite people and foster connection. This was a formative memory from his early days living in the Mission.\n\n5. Guiding an older adult through a gentle sculpting exercise, watching their hands, stiff with age and trauma, slowly relax as they shaped the clay. The quiet sigh of release when they finished, the subtle smile \u2013 it was a privilege. This tiny moment of shared vulnerability solidified the quiet power of patience and compassionate presence in his work. This memory is from a specific therapeutic session early in his established career."
